close_symbols: typedefs for uint32_t / uint8_t (stdint.h typedefs used)
explanation: 1) struct SHA1Context (complete definition): Required to see the exact types and qualifiers of members (especially message_block, intermediate_hash, message_block_index). To assess MISRA 'pointer should point to const when possible' we must know which members are modified by other code and which are read-only here: if some members (e.g. message_block contents) are only read they might be const-qualified inside the struct or accessed via a pointer-to-const. Conversely, any member modified (intermediate_hash[], message_block_index) proves the context pointer cannot be const. 2) SHA1CircularShift (declaration/prototype): Although called with scalar arguments here, its prototype ensures it does not take pointer parameters or perform hidden modifications via pointers. If it took pointer args or returned pointer-to-memory, that could affect whether data must be non-const. 3) SHA1PadMessage (declaration and implementation): A caller of SHA1ProcessMessageBlock — needed to determine how context is passed elsewhere (as const or non-const) and whether callers modify the context fields. If callers require non-const context, that constrains whether pointer types can be changed. 4) SHA1Input (declaration and implementation): Same reason as SHA1PadMessage — it is a caller; its signature and implementation show whether the context object is modified elsewhere, which impacts whether members or the context pointer could be const. 5) typedefs for uint32_t / uint8_t (stdint.h typedefs used): To confirm the exact base types (signedness/width) of message_block and intermediate_hash elements and ensure no hidden pointer/const interactions via type aliases.
